@ace Most networked multiplayer games of the late '90s and early '00s were P2P. People complained about the potential for cheating when Id Software open sourced Quake II. John Carmack's response:

"I'm sure I will catch some flack about increased cheating after the source release, but there are plenty of Q2 cheats already out there, so you are already in the position of having to trust the other players to a degree. The problem is really only solvable by relying on the community to police itself, because it is a fundamentally unwinnable technical battle to make a completely cheat proof game of this type. Play with your friends."

The P2P part is actually a red herring, though. Sure, you can use some heuristics server-side to try to catch cheaters, but it doesn't really matter that much if scores aren't worth anything and you don't incentivize cheating by making some kind of leaderboard. In fact, cheats could even make a game more fun by giving new ways to play the game, or people could compete by writing bots. Or you could even build a game around writing bots.
